You seem to think that the first parameter is what specifies the interfaces that the proxy object implements. This is not true - specifying the interfaces that the proxy should implement is the job of the second parameter. You can give multiple interfaces, as a `Class[]`, to say that the proxy should implement.

The first argument specifies what class loader should be used to define the proxy object&#39;s class.

See https://stackoverflow.com/q/2424604/5133585 if you don&#39;t understand what a class loader is.

In your example, `IHello.class.getClassLoader()` is passed as the first parameter. The fact that `IHello.class` appears in this expression has nothing to do with what interfaces we want the proxy to implement. `IHello.class.getClassLoader()` just gets the class loader that loaded `IHello`. I could also pass `ClassLoader.getSystemClassLoader()`, or my own implementation of `ClassLoader` as the first parameter.

All that matters is that the first parameter is a class loader, and it satisfies some requirements, listed in the [documentation][1]. The most relevant ones for this question would be:

&gt; - All of the interface types must be visible by name through the specified class loader.
&gt; - All of the types referenced by all public method signatures of the specified interfaces and those inherited by their superinterfaces must
&gt; be visible by name through the specified class loader.

`newProxyInstance` would throw an exception if any of the requirements are not met.

You often see people doing `SomeInterface.class.getClassLoader()`, and then also passing `SomeInterface.class` as the second parameter, because `SomeInterface` is trivially &quot;visible by name&quot; through the class loader that loaded `SomeInterface`, so it definitely satisfies the requirements.

As an additional example, here is a call to `newProxyInstance` that would throw an exception:

```
Proxy.newProxyInstance(String.class.getClassLoader(),
        new Class[] { I.class },
        (a, b, c) -&gt; {
            System.out.println(&quot;Foo&quot;);
            return true;
        });

// ...

interface I {}
```

Here, `String.class` is loaded by the platform class loader (because it is a JDK class), but `I` is loaded by the system class loader, as it is an interface I wrote.



  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/reflect/Proxy.html#newProxyInstance(java.lang.ClassLoader,java.lang.Class%5B%5D,java.lang.reflect.InvocationHandler)

