The argument of `@Query` is the only the query part of a search request, not any sorting or filter parameters (please use text blocks instead of theat unreadable `\&quot;` escaping). You have to pass these with an additional parameter of the type `Sort`:

````java
@Query(&quot;&quot;&quot;
				{
					&quot;bool&quot;: {
						&quot;should&quot;: [
							{
								&quot;match&quot;: {&quot;name&quot;: &quot;?0&quot;}
							},
							{
								&quot;match&quot;: {&quot;email&quot;: &quot;?1&quot;}
							},
							{
								&quot;match&quot;: {&quot;address&quot;: &quot;?2&quot;}
							},
							{
								&quot;match&quot;: {&quot;phone&quot;: &quot;?3&quot;}
							}
						]
					}
				}
				&quot;&quot;&quot;)
List&lt;User&gt; partialSearch(String name, String email, String address, String phone, Sort sort);
````

At the place where this method is called you build the Sort like this:
````java
var sort = Sort.by(sortField).ascending(); // or use .descending()
var users = partialSearch(name, email, address, phone, sort)

````

As an alternative for specifiying the query part for a simple search like this, you could just define a repository method like this:
````java
List&lt;Users&gt; findByNameAndEmailAndAddressAndPhone(String, name, String email, String address, String phone, Sort sort);
````
and let Spring Data Elasticsearch handle the query building, see the [reference documentation](https://docs.spring.io/spring-data/elasticsearch/docs/current/reference/html/#elasticsearch.query-methods)

